Remove the modules and tests that have moved to oslo.log. Replace the
use of oslo.log with the standard library logging module.

Replace calls to LOG.deprecated() with a new function in versionutils
that is copied from the body of the old implementation.

Add fatal_deprecations configuration option to versionutils, where it is
used now instead of the old log module.

Closes-Bug: #1373120

commit_message:
Remove oslo.log code and clean up versionutils API

Remove the modules and tests that have moved to oslo.log. Replace the
use of oslo.log with the standard library logging module.

Replace calls to LOG.deprecated() with a new function in versionutils
that is copied from the body of the old implementation.

Add fatal_deprecations configuration option to versionutils, where it is
used now instead of the old log module.

Change-Id: I5903f9a9c521789cbf3381d9741a8a5308767e2d
Closes-Bug: #1373120
Blueprint: fix-import-cycle-log-and-versionutils

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-01-29 06:00:19.000000000', 'message': "driver: Register ganesha specific config options

To allow the instances of classes (e.g. GPFSShareDriver) that inherit
GaneshaMixin and ShareDriver classes to also have ganesha specific
configuration options, the initialization method of the ShareDriver
class is supposed to call the init_ganesha_mixin() method of the
GaneshaMixin class, but currently fails to do so. The initialization
method instead incorrectly calls ExecuteMixin class's
init_execute_mixin() method. So fix this.

Change-Id: Iafbdcf7ff1701f95e62f444602a5a2d38ad82938
Closes-Bug: #1415738
"}, {'created': '2015-01-29 17:13:49.000000000', 'message': "driver: Fix ganesha config option registry

To register the ganesha config options, the initialization method of
the ShareDriver class incorrectly calls the ExecuteMixin class's
init_execute_mixin() method. Instead call GaneshaMixin's
init_ganesha_mixin() method.

Change-Id: Iafbdcf7ff1701f95e62f444602a5a2d38ad82938
Closes-Bug: #1415738
"}]
commit_message:
driver: Fix ganesha config option registry

To register the ganesha config options, the initialization method of
the ShareDriver class incorrectly calls the ExecuteMixin class's
init_execute_mixin() method. Instead call GaneshaMixin's
init_ganesha_mixin() method.

Change-Id: Iafbdcf7ff1701f95e62f444602a5a2d38ad82938
Closes-Bug: #1415738

As the commit message mentioned, current *v2.0* API is too complex and not readable. I agree with that.

However, we have already implemented *v2.1* API for solving this kind of problems as the framework and its development has been almost done now.
The code of v2.1 is very clean because each extension parameters(max_count, etc) are handled in each extension class(not in common part like this) and we can remove extension handling methods from common part.
In addition, this "create a server" API is very important for OpenStack. So I don't think now is right time for changing it. It seems high risk even if getting a little benefit at the end of this cycle.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-12-05 16:02:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I tend to agree with Ken'ichi here, however, I believe the reason this is being done (and is not called out as the reason for doing this change in the commit message), is to drop the max complexity threshold in tox.ini:

mriedem@ubuntu:~/git/nova$ tox -e pep8
pep8 develop-inst-nodeps: /home/mriedem/git/nova
pep8 runtests: PYTHONHASHSEED='0'
pep8 runtests: commands[0] | flake8
./nova/api/openstack/compute/servers.py:769:1: C901 'Controller.create' is too complex (46)

This is currently the next most complex thing we have in the code base so to keep wittling down on complexity we'd have to clean this up.  I'm also a bit loath to refactor the v2 server create API, but we're kind of unwilling to ever enforce complexity < 47 w/o this.

I've added jogo for his thoughts."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-12-11 19:41:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Split Controller.create in servers.py to private methods

'Controller.create' in /nova/api/openstack/compute/servers.py
is too complex, break out some of the guts into private methods.

Change-Id: I87dda4d38f62bbd50f6079e24340487fe40c883e
Closes-bug: #1390421

commit_message:
Fixes blocking of VRF config in Arista L3 Plugin

This fix removes the restriction that Arista HW,
when configured in MLAG (redunancy) mode, is not
allowed to configure in VRF mode.

Additionally, a minor fix to log message is made
as the correct message is logged when an
exception is hit.

cherry picked for back-port to stable/juno

Closes-bug: 1411016

(cherry picked from commit: Icc1e9cc81d20c6aa19ed0429bdbc781e4a11f224)

Conflicts:
	neutron/plugins/ml2/drivers/arista/arista_l3_driver.py

Change-Id: I707727e95300c27375f4f23fdca62fef304e9b16

commit_message:
Maintain the creation order for vifs

Ensure that the backend and the front end keep the vifs in the
same order that they were specified in when they were created.

Closes-Bug: 1405271
Change-Id: If6e1dc51609c764de8352b933b7a847952d08931

commit_message:
Catch more specific exception in _get_power_state

_get_power_state expects InstanceNotFound and not its parent exception
NotFound.  So catch the more specific exception to make the code
consistent and so we don't hide other issues.

Change-Id: I64b79d954f1b48d073b0a4662a58c803425c015f
Closes-Bug: #1400764

[{'created': '2014-12-19 12:51:42.000000000', 'message': "Update WSGI SSL IPv6 test and SSL certificates

Switch the WSGI SSL IPv6 test from urllib2 to Request because of
Python 2.7.9 changes and provide a server SSL certificate that
supports IPv6.

The test failed on Python 2.7.9 because Python now verifies SSL
connections by default (PEP 466) and the test CA certificate was not
provided to verify the SSL connection.  Passing urllib2.urlopener the
test CA certificate through the new new cafile parameter allows Python
to verify the SSL connection, but is not compatible with prior
versions of Python.  Requests supports using a CA file regardless of
Python 2.7 version.

Once using Requests and the test CA certificate to verify the SSL
connection the test continued to fail because the previous certificate
only specified an IPv4 address, specifically in the deprecated Common
Name field, which is unsuitable for verifying an IPv6 address.

    Error: hostname '::1' doesn't match u'0.0.0.0'

A new certificate was created with a wildcard in the Common Name
field, but primarily depends on IPv4 and IPv6 localhost names and
addresses in the Subject Alternative Name field to accommodate a
variety of test scenarios and in line with industry practices (see RFC
2818).

The old CA's private key was not available to sign the new server
certificate so a new CA certificate was generated and it's public and
private keys are provided.

Change-Id: I990d5b5b57d1b5c569aa86828364b3a762d149e1

commit_message:
Update WSGI SSL IPv6 test and SSL certificates

Switch the WSGI SSL IPv6 test from urllib2 to Requests because of
Python 2.7.9 changes and provide a server SSL certificate that
supports IPv6.

The test failed on Python 2.7.9 because Python now verifies SSL
connections by default (PEP 466) and the test CA certificate was not
provided to verify the SSL connection.  Passing urllib2.urlopener the
test CA certificate through the new cafile parameter allows Python to
verify the SSL connection, but is not compatible with prior versions
of Python.  Requests supports using a CA file regardless of Python 2.7
version.

Once using Requests and the test CA certificate to verify the SSL
connection the test continued to fail because the previous certificate
only specified an IPv4 address, specifically in the deprecated Common
Name field, which is unsuitable for verifying an IPv6 address.

    Error: hostname '::1' doesn't match u'0.0.0.0'

A new certificate was created with a wildcard in the Common Name
field, but primarily depends on IPv4 and IPv6 localhost names and
addresses in the Subject Alternative Name field to accommodate a
variety of test scenarios and in line with industry practices (see RFC
2818).

The old CA's private key was not available to sign the new server
certificate so a new CA certificate was generated and it's public and
private keys are provided.

Closes-Bug: #1404390

Change-Id: I990d5b5b57d1b5c569aa86828364b3a762d149e1

commit_message:
Make _get_instance_block_device_info preserve root_device_name

On hard reboots,
nova.compute.manager.ComputeManager._get_instance_block_device_info will
faithfully reconstruct all of the block_device_info attributes that
the instance needs, except for the root_device_name.  This causes
the instance to effectively lose its disk configurations on hard
reboots.

This patch set will preserve the root_device_name if it is defined
for the instance.

Closes-Bug: #1378132
Change-Id: Ia36b1d6170ad120f794aa16d41ed4275b4b11f22

commit_message:
Make agent config available to the router classes

Since the agent and the routers are all configured in the same config
file, the routers are going to need access to the agent's config.
This work will support multiple future patches.

Change-Id: I33a23eb37678d94cea3ace8afe090935b1e70685
Partially-Implements: bp/restructure-l3-agent

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary reference to nova-network in Hyper-V docs

The config-reference page for the Hyper-V Virtualization Platform
makes a reference to nova-network. Since the guide assumes neutron
will be used, there is no need for such a reference.

Closes-Bug: #1415882
Change-Id: Ia766edad76d096b3d95b7f7485467648e51a66ac
(cherry picked from commit a88ac02a010f1afa40dd0a642a890f59b45b914c)

commit_message:
Add find_unique base manager method

Allows to request a single matched item from list of resources,
raising NotFound if no match was found or Conflict if more than one
match was found.

Change-Id: Ib8b516d96de2b95ae20eb4545db12c0b82651941
Closes-Bug: #1414953

commit_message:
Make the interface driver available to the router classes

Ultimately, it will only be the routers that need access to the
interface driver and the agent won't need to use it for anything.
However, it still makes sense for the agent to initialize it once and
pass it to each of the routers as they're created.

Multiple patches with multiple authors will be created to depend on
this addition.

Change-Id: I0ec75d731d816955c1915e283a137abcb51ac232
Partially-Implements: bp/restructure-l3-agent

commit_message:
Add funcName to audit/info message output

When trying to get a handle on a bug it is very frustrating to get a
log message that could have come from multiple places and be unable to
disambiguate them.  For example in [1] the last clue was an AUDIT
message that might have come from one of two places in the same file.
See [2] for an example of the issue in oslo.

AUDIT and INFO level messages do give their name, but it doesn't help
when the duplication is with a file.  It seems reasonable to always
log the function name to avoid this.

[1] https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1084833
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/87442/

Change-Id: Ib59d77d94d9d0d5c0d2867c09f46784242633c19

commit_message:
Fixes unicode logging decoding issue

Logging fails with an exception when unicode conversion of the message
cannot be performed.

This includes also Exception objects, where the exception message has
an unknown encoding.

The calling code should be responsible for handling the unicode encoding, but
nevertheless, the logging module should handle this scenario and not raise
an exception.

Closes-Bug: #1393870

Change-Id: I31671974101935254deb0b843904e344b4666f3d

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary reference to nova-network in Hyper-V docs

The config-reference page for the Hyper-V Virtualization Platform
makes a reference to nova-network. Since the guide assumes neutron
will be used, there is no need for such a reference.

Change-Id: Ia766edad76d096b3d95b7f7485467648e51a66ac
Closes-Bug: #1415882

commit_message:
Move policy parser to a separate module.

This moves the policy code in charge of rules
parsing and checking into a separate file "policy_parser.py".

"policy_parser.py" file is aimed to be self-sufficient and
independent from other oslo modules. For that global objects
like LOG, _(gettext) and jsonutils have been componized i.e
users can set their own version on those objects (assuming
that they provide the same services).

The result is:
 * A module that can be used as it is in other projects
   independently from other oslo modules.
 * backward compatible: The enforcer class in charge of loading
   and checking rules have been kept the same in policy.py
   module.

The purpose is to facilitate the use of the policy parser
in other project, and hopefully will facilitate graduate
oslo.policy as well.

implements bp generalize-policy-engine

Change-Id: I392c534aab42f01095d3293a053f44f19daf9de0

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-01-29 15:31:14.000000000', 'message': "Add unaliased mod name to import_aliases; Fix tests

In order to identify what module an imported symbol came from
we need to be able to look it up in the list of imported symbols
for the module. These symbols could be aliased but don't
have to be. In both case we want to be able to look it up.
We handled when an symbol was aliased on import, but not
when it wasn't. This meant we could not get a true fully
qualified name for that symbol at its point of use.

For example:
  import a from b as c
  import d from e

  import_aliases['c'] = a.b
  import_aliases['e'] = d.e # new behavior

  c() # qualified as a.b
  e() # qualified as d.e

To fix an imported symbol that is not aliased is still added
to import_aliases with its real name. The primary danger
is the code overriding the imported symbol with a local
name definition. We don't catch that, but it is less common.

commit_message:
Add unaliased mod name to import_aliases; Fix tests

In order to identify what module an imported symbol came from
we need to be able to look it up in the list of imported symbols
for the module. These symbols could be aliased but don't
have to be. In both case we want to be able to look it up.
We handled when an symbol was aliased on import, but not
when it wasn't. This meant we could not get a true fully
qualified name for that symbol at its point of use.

For example:
  import a from b as c
  import d from e

  import_aliases['c'] = a.b
  import_aliases['e'] = d.e # new behavior

  c() # qualified as a.b
  e() # qualified as d.e

To fix an imported symbol that is not aliased is still added
to import_aliases with its real name. The primary danger
is the code overriding the imported symbol with a local
name definition. We don't catch that, but it is less common.

This causes tests for os_popen, mktemp, and ssl-insecure-verion
to fail. In the first two tests, additional calls are identified
as problems. For the ssl test, we updated the test to look for
the fully qualified name pyOpenSSL.SSL.Context.

For other tests:
examples/os-popen.py:
  master was missing line 7 'popen()' which was imported from os.
  We can now catch this.

examples/mktemp.py:
  master was missing line 10 'mktemp(foo)' which was imported from
  tempfile. The blacklist specified tempfile.mktemp so this was missed.

Change-Id: I487bace2e4c9daaf5ab75fc8e351c3b990532e3a

commit_message:
Removing imports of classes instead of modules

The import of classes instead of python modules was causing Jenkins pep8 to
fail due to H302 error, as in:
http://logs.openstack.org/82/141382/3/check/gate-monasca-api-pep8/1303b90/console.html

commit_message:
Make role manager refer to role cache config options

The role manager was using the general assignment cache options
rather than the role specific cache options in the config. This
patch fixes this.

Change-Id: I4c6d1c146cf75d47cc258ef6a4d59848c6f75313
Closes-Bug: 1415959

subject: Decrease oslo.config minimum version requirement
revisions:
[{'created': '2015-01-29 18:32:40.000000000', 'message': 'Decrease oslo.config minimum version requirement

This commit decreases the minimum required version for oslo.config
from 1.6.0 to 1.2.0 to support stable/icehouse which supports
oslo.config>=1.2.0,<1.5 (from requirements).

Change-Id: I1eb9eb8bba49e8844945bb808b7592269cda9144
Closes-Bug: #1415243
'}]
commit_message:
Decrease oslo.config minimum version requirement

This commit decreases the minimum required version for oslo.config
from 1.6.0 to 1.2.0 to support stable/icehouse which supports
oslo.config>=1.2.0,<1.5 (from requirements).

Change-Id: I1eb9eb8bba49e8844945bb808b7592269cda9144
Closes-Bug: #1415243

commit_message:
password visibility icon not shown for first page

In the initial page (http://<ip>:<port>) the
password field not showing the password visibility
icon.

If we go to login page (http://<ip>:<port>/auth/login)
the password visibility icon is shown properly.

Now both the address are using the same template so
the password visibility icon shown in the initial
page also and the unused template is deleted.

Change-Id: Ia8063c54143c5394c927cf7aea7c15c3e9373dd0
Closes-Bug: #1408220

just merged. If there's a defined endpoint for any one of the specified

empty string being returned rather than picking up the general endpoint.

commit_message:
specific_endpoint can return incorrect values

There's a bug in the common library specific_endpoint routine that
was just merged. If there's a defined endpoint for any one of the
specified types ('internal', 'admin', 'public') it causes the code
to incorrectly think that any name of that same type actually
exists.  This leads to an empty string being returned rather than
picking up the general endpoint.

For example:
['endpoints']['admin']['foo'] has been set
['endpoints']['bar'] has been set

The admin_endpoint('bar') routine should see that there's no 'bar'
under 'admin' and return the general endpoint. Instead, it's
returning an empty string simply because there's an 'admin' subhash
there for 'foo'.

Change-Id: Ifd4ee6108b4c7b0f66bd56cc817b5ea646e82a68
Partial-Bug: 1412919

Please do let me know if you disagree."}, {'account_id': 13734, 'date': '2014-10-31 13:41:03.000000000', 'content': 'Topic changed from bp/vif-type-routed to bp/vif-type-tap'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2014-11-20 12:49:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

(5 comments)

This probably needed to be discussed at the summit in the nova unconference track.

We can schedule a google hangout to discuss this if needed.

My key worry is how using this model fits into Nova's move to depend on Neutron for all networking.

It feels like the first step is to get neutron to model this kind of networking, then create a neutron "agent" that configures the compute hosts routing, that can then be connected to the appropriate VIFs.

One the neutron work is in place, I don't mind this going into Nova. Maybe this is a bit "chicken and egg"'}, {'account_id': 13734, 'date': '2014-11-20 16:20:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

(5 comments)

Hi John,

Many thanks for your review!

Regarding your key worry about the split of networking responsibility between Nova and Neutron...  We absolutely want to implement the Project Calico fabric idea within the Neutron model, and by offering a minimal set of deltas to the Neutron codebase in order to enable what we need.  (And please note that this spec does reference two related Neutron specs, which describe those deltas.)

We've only proposed this Nova change, in addition, because we couldn't see any other way of getting a plain TAP interface - without any bridging or such like - to a VM.  However, if there _is_ already a way of doing that, either using existing Nova or Neutron code, or in a way that doesn't need to change Nova, we would be very interested to look at that instead, and to drop this spec.

You suggested a hangout to discuss further, and it would be great to do that.  When would be good for you?  Also I guess you might be based in Cambridge, and I am there too for some of the week, so we could even meet in person...

I've also responded to your specific comments - please see below and in the spec revision.

Best wishes,
    Neil"}, {'account_id': 13734, 'date': '2014-12-06 02:36:50.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-12-06 02:40:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

commit_message:
New VIF type to allow routing VM data instead of bridging it

We propose to add a new VIF type, VIF_TYPE_TAP, whose meaning is that
the host side of a VNIC to a VM is - at least initially - a simple TAP
interface that is not plugged into a bridge or vSwitch.  A Neutron
agent can continue the process of deciding how to handle data from
that interface, and how to deliver data to it - but this is beyond the
scope of the initial TAP interface setup that Nova needs to provide.

Change-Id: I7bd6e07b8e4e1279e2c4098d2c75896a470dcfef

commit_message:
Save input parameters for stack adopt.

While issuing a stack-adopt, the input parameters (supplied with -P
option) are required to be saved. The input parameters override the
parameters given in adopt template.

 Closes-Bug: #1350908

Change-Id: I7419363354e3ef97f426a327573336eafb8e15ba

commit_message:
Store auth_url and region_name when trusts are enabled

We don't currently store auth_url, which causes problems when creating
autoscaling groups containing servers configured for software config,
because we use context.auth_url to populate the auth_url in the server
metadata, which is needed by the deployments for signalling.

Also adding region_name, as this seems likely to be needed for correct
operation in a multi-region environment.

Closes-Bug: #1415901
Change-Id: I550d03ea1b6985ba0777bf5ca52c79a8e8e60f5a

commit_message:
Fix the neutron-vpnaas unit test failures

The neutron commit (274c66f291f40224e3f16dcdf02b17ccb1196924)
has changed the init params of router_info.RouterInfo, because
of which some neutron-vpnaas unit tests are failing.

This patch fixes those failures.

Change-Id: I6d3c7da7a3f5eb261efe722ac65f4297dad94edb
Closes-bug: #1415891

commit_message:
Add a moved *instance* method deprecation pattern

When an instance method has moved to a better location (for
whatever reason) it is nice to provide the old instance method
under the previous name for a deprecation cycle. To enable
this kind of pattern use/modify/extend the existing moved decorator
to not just work for properties but also work for instance methods.

Change-Id: Ie002d9255d9e5127011c5308c7f5ce16d0b44821

commit_message:
Add role for tempest to allow set image location

Recent glance policy additions prevent non admins from setting image
location and therefore creating remote images. Tempest users need this
functionality, so this patch adds a role to those users and a policy to
allow that role to set image location.

The change that allows users to specify roles to be added to tempest
users has already been merged upstream:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/147542/

In order to use the upstream tempest changes, I had to bump the tempest
sha, which in turn required some client package upgrades:

 * tempest to 3feb4d4e1f9367269a226f788ff468f820751340
 * python-glanceclient to 0.15.0
 * python-saharaclient to 0.7.6

Change-Id: I9ed053bf70680db54b1cf679a171d61ea639f19d
Closes-Bug: #1411599

While I'm generally ok with proposed fix I have some concerns that I think should be taken into account:

Existing _ensure method will do a reconnect in case of publish exception. I don't think that this is what we want in our case since there is no logical reason to reconnect producer. Reconnect operation is quite expensive and may cause unnecessary degradation of QoS. I think that we may need to update our error handling to take this case into account (possibly introduce something like RetryException?). What do you think?"}, {'account_id': 8772, 'date': '2014-07-24 21:33:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

If the producer doesn't retry and reconnect, we're depending on the consumer timing out and retrying, which would be bad:

1. consumer sends
2. producer receives
3. producer does RPC call
4. producer fails to send to rabbit, aborts
5. consumer times out (~10-60sec)
6. consumer retries... maybe.  goto 1

This is worse than the producer retrying because:

- #5 introduces a long delay in the rpc call
- the rpc work in #3 gets executed twice (usually more expensive than rabbit reconnect)
- the consumer may not retry at all.  That's what's happening in the current bug: producer delivers to a nonexistent queue, consumer never retries rpc."}, {'account_id': 7763, 'date': '2014-07-24 21:44:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hi,

I think the flow you provided is missing several important steps:

Let's try to describe both normal and failover scenarios step by step (and later post it on gerrit or somewhere else)

Glossary:
client - RPCClient object sends RPC call
server - MessageHandlingServer object recives RPC call, dispatches it in python, sends replies

Normal:
* client sends call message
* server receives and dispatches call
* server sends reply message
* client receives reply
* PROFIT

Failover (the case we are trying to fix)
* client sends call message
* server receives and dispatches call
* FAILOVER happens here (connection to messaging broker is lost)
* server reconnects
* server sends reply message (declares exchange but not the queue)
* client reconnects and redeclares exchange and queue (message is already lost since published to empty exchange)
* Timeout exception

Failover (with your patch)
* client sends call message
* server receives and dispatches call
* FAILOVER happens here (connection to messaging broker is lost)
* server reconnects
* server tries to probe exchange existence (and fails since it doesn't exist)
* server falls into reconnect loop waiting for client to declare exchange
* client reconnects and redeclares exchange and queue
* server sends reply message
* client receives reply
* PROFIT

So my concern here is "server falls into reconnect loop waiting for client to declare exchange" There is no need for server to reconnect since it has already happend. Duration of reconnect loop is also not limited since we don't know when the client will declare needed exchange (and it may never happen) this will cause the server process to hang forever.
I think this is not what we want and here is my proposals:
* reconnect can be replaced with simple sleep (since server is already connected)
* publish retry loop should be limited to some reasonable number

Furthermore our driver doesn't know what message it's trying to send (rpc request, rpc reply or whatever) I'm not sure that same publish retry approach would work well in all cases.
This bug is actually much deeper than it may seem and it requires careful planning and choosing appropriate behavior for all cases.

To tell the truth I actually think that it may be better to not fix it at all. Service that is using oslo.messaging should be prepared to the case that some messages may be lost and handle such cases in some kind of fault tolerant way. It would be much more logical in long term since the same approach is required for many other actions (db failover, etc.)

Possibly we should escalate this discussion to dev-list.
It would be good to hear the views of representatives of oslo.messaging users about what behavior should be considered correct.

Please correct me If I'm wrong in describing the situation (or elsewhere).

Regards,
Alexei Kornienko'}, {'account_id': 8772, 'date': '2014-07-25 15:48:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

The server should give up eventually if the client never recreates the
queue.  However, there's no way to pass a timeout from direct_send()
to Publisher.reconnect().  The server will never give up if the client
never redeclares the queue.  That's not good.

Getting the server to fail and retry the exchange declaration would be
tighter than throwing away the whole rabbit connection and
reconnecting.  Putting a retry loop around the exchange declaration
could exceed the timeout used to abort the whole send operation.

I'd recommend:

1. Adding a timeout argument to direct_send() and setting the
   timeout... somewhere?  in AMQPIncomingMessage._send_reply()?  In
   direct_send()?  Where's the best place to configure the timeout?

2. The fact that the client doesn't retry if the server fails to
   deliver the reply should be a separate bug.

How does that sound to you?

If a client is restarted, it will regenerate a unique name for its reply queue and the old reply queue will (at present at least) be autodeleted. However if it had any requests outstanding, the name of the old reply-queue would still be in those. The server replying to the stale request would continue to fail to publish the message since the old exchange and queue would no longer exist and would never be created.

(Also, since the exchange is declared by the consumer before it has bound the queue, there is still a window - admittedly very small - where a message can be published to an existing exchange before the queue is actually bound.)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-19 11:22:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Verified+1

Gordon, that's not correct.  This problem is not when a client restarts, but when *rabbit* restarts.  The client continues running and reconnects with the same reply_q uuid as before.  Then problem is, the consumer may reconnect after the producer reconnects, and some people object to the producer re-creating the reply queue.

This would be simpler if RPC was done without rabbit in the middle, but these protocol tweaks are necessary to handle the case where the messsage broker dies and restarts, not the RPC client or server."}, {'account_id': 8784, 'date': '2014-08-20 08:11:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

Noel,

Yes I understand that is the use case your fix is for. However the issue I was pointing out was different it was that when the client restarts you may have outstanding requests with reply-to addresses referring to autodeleted queue/exchange.

This is the issue that you created https://review.openstack.org/#/c/110511/ for. I hadn't seen that review yet at the time I responded to this one.

--Gordon."}, {'account_id': 7536, 'date': '2014-09-02 15:48:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Declare DirectPublisher exchanges with passive=True

If rabbit dies, the consumer can be disconnected before the publisher
sends, and if the consumer hasn't declared the queue, the publisher's
will send a message to an exchange that's not bound to a queue, and
the message wll be lost.  Setting passive=True will cause the
publisher to fail and retry if the consumer hasn't declared the
receiving queue yet.

Co-Authored-By: Noel Burton-Krahn <noel@burton-krahn.com>
Closes-Bug: #1338732
Change-Id: I5ba4d311b97236d3a85a9f5badff61f12b08c12d

commit_message:
Initial import of renames/moves + tests

This adds the initial import (and adjustments to requirements
and code) that was initially targeted to land into oslo.utils
but now lands in this project from the following:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/140119

This forms the basis of the debtcollector functionality (with
more to come as/when needed).

Change-Id: Icd62622a728525fab48ba4de7ee746d0add73b9b

commit_message:
Specify units in haproxy configuration

Previous update omitted the 's' suffix so the value was interpreted as
miliseconds. This patch corrects that.

Change-Id: Ie7fa32a472105b2e7ba1074122b3abd8b4467f4c
Closes-Bug: #1402580
(cherry picked from commit 8c2f84bd8a9ea049cf05016790d96e4f8e4a8dbd)

commit_message:
oslo.messaging: Move gate hooks to oslo.msg tree

We have to keep in sync the configuration and the credentials
of the rpc driver between gate and oslo.messaging funcionnal tests.

To do this we move the custom devstack setup to oslo.messaging.

oslo.messaging part: https://review.openstack.org/151191

Change-Id: I6adafc9d182767f259af18f75f76f9496b564f52

commit_message:
Limit the keys support in dict field type

Sometimes we want the dict to include only limited keys, so that
if a field created with invalid key, it will be wrong. One example
is CPU topology, which can be only socket, core and thread.

Change-Id: Id525aaf47da41d7a4126fa135f31caf403a7bb00

commit_message:
Use --no-defaults with mysql database creation

Otherwise configuration from an extant my.cnf can be used and
the database will be created in the primary mysql service, not
the one being used for tests.

Change-Id: I0f3b382fc2a348e1e857cfecb6cfa573b90d9a2d

commit_message:
Workaround Nova VM boot bug

Generic driver is unable to boot VMs anymore. The cause is in appeared bug in
Nova, that was introduced by commit d8cafb9a6efb95b78609aca8fcb3532c33a1788f,
where Nova is unable to boot VM if port from Neutron is provided.

Checkout Nova working commit until this bug is fixed in Nova.

Change-Id: I6dd2892392b5d08a7cede9c750d6328bee7dea9b
Closes-Bug: #1415770

Remove useless and unused request_utils

This code is not used and has never been used by Cinder, let's remove
it as it is safe to do so. It's not imported anywhere.

Change-Id: I963caebb304d2211755164a082fc600a9570dd1e

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Re-generate rsyslog conf after all swift plays

Adjust swift-all playbook to re-generate the openstack.conf for rsyslog
such that all swift logs are included and forwarded to logstash
appropriately.

Change-Id: Ieab900b90ccd597c1ff4a9f5fc0422bb63f23ed8
Closes-Bug: #1415046

commit_message:
Adds unit tests for HNAS backend

HNAS drivers only have unit tests for the driver classes. The backend class
used to interface with the array didn't had unit tests.

Change-Id: I1f27533bf6890f033602abdcde33bb42e49c2851

commit_message:
Fix use of actual vs. expected

In https://review.openstack.org/#/c/147256/5/sanity_check_version.py,cm
it was pointed out that the use of "actual" and "expected" for variable
names seemed backwards here. Reverse their use, and add a missing test
to verify that the old check for a minor version being incremented
too far was broken but is now fixed by the name reversal.

Change-Id: Ia9a2139ac3a6bf4c289b9f90356993beaa7961a7

commit_message:
Add retry to lvm snapshot create

We have some occasional issues with snapshot-create
failing for what looks to be conflicts with udev.  It
looks like this problem is a status conflict between LVM
cache and udev, and in most cases the best way to get
around this is to retry the command a few times until
the cache and udev are back in sync.

This patch uses the newly added retry decorator and
for now we're just adding it to the snapshot create
call.  We're using the default values for interval and
retry count but we can certainly adjust this as needed.

Change-Id: Ic884b829591361da979fde968f5710237b34565f
Closes-Bug: #1335905

commit_message:
Fetch_to_volume_format calls copy_volume using wrong parameter

When creating a volume from an image, if qemu-img is not installed,
fetch_to_volume_format will call volume_utils.copy_volume to copy
image to volume. Copy_volume need the size of image in megabyte,
but fetch_to_volume_format call it using size in bytes.

Change-Id: Ia3b0f9168235a977a12232e27a5755ad11ec18f5
Closes-Bug: #1414867

commit_message:
Fix metering daily display

For Icehouse and Juno ,add " {% load url from future %}" to
openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/metering/templates/metering/daily.html,
so template rendering can resolve horizon url variables

Since this page in Kilo has been refactored,it does not have this problem.

Closes-Bug: #1324218
Change-Id: Ic52b1130fbe744caa1c1082037f139529513410a

commit_message:
Increase Glance container LV size

Setting the Glance container LV size to 12GB to account for default glance-cache "image_cache_max_size".

The default glance "image_cache_max_size" in glance_cache.conf is 10GB. Having the default container size less than this can create issues.

Change-Id: I5fd36c5c05398b7cf2369fa581fc059f6632a7a1
Closes-Bug: 1403584

commit_message:
Remove URL field from regions

With the advent of the service provider concept, there
is no need to maintain the URL field from the regions
object since it was used only to map an external
service provider.

bp k2k-service-providers

Change-Id: Ibcc5778b5ac7b014a74593b41c30eb046e33f7b1

commit_message:
Make digest algorithm configurable

It would be great to enhance Glance to use minimum of SHA2
to do digital signature for FIPS compliance. Since in
FIPS(FEDERAL INFORMATION PROCESSING STANDARDS) says the
SHA-1 is not suitable for general-purpose digital signature
applications (as specified in FIPS 186-3) that require 112
bits of security. In the case of digital signatures, SHA-1
does not provide the 112 bits of collision resistance needed
to achieve the security strength.

Now we're using hardcode 'sha1'. So this patch will make it
configurable firstly and set the default value as sha1 in
Kilo for smooth upgrade, which will be changed with sha256
in next release(L).

DocImpact
UpgradeImapact
SecurityImpact

Closes-Bug: #1288545

Change-Id: I9236cc85f4e9881ac1aa35d69bc6761a59c1b6c8

commit_message:
VMware: mark cloned virtual machines as 'belonging' to OpenStack

Commit f4fec08e9850dae163f447e72cd1c7f638b2bb10 marked VMs as 'belonging'
to OpenStack. An instance that was resized was not marked.

Closes-bug: #1402784

Change-Id: I66565cc7bcb835e448232e8eaeb010a792dade5f

(1 comment)

Another thing I didn't like when using this script is that it tags with gerrit first; which means if the later parts of the script are borked (the launchpad stuff) basically you can't re-run this script (since the gerrit tag will already be created)... Whats your thought on doing the gerrit tag last (and/or checking if its already tagged and skipping) so that the script is able to be ran again and again if failures happen (which I did cause once, ha, and had to comment out parts to get it to resume without breaking...)."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-01-15 08:00:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Yay tests! This is getting serious.

The debug comment that Josh picked up should be fixed. Otherwise looks good.

@Joshua: the scripts implement the release process so I'd rather have the tag happen first. That said, the release scripts need to get better at being retried in case of later failure. In that precise case, we should not error out if the tag is already there, just ask for confirmation. That should not be held against that specific change imho, since that's an issue in all the other release scripts too :)"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-01-15 19:21:19.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-01-15 19:22:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Add sanity check script for new version tags

Add a script to catch a few common errors in new version numbers to give
the user a chance to avoid them. Set up tox and testr to support tests
for the new script.

Change-Id: I2a48f3de3886821611f370e04c9be13ada67edbf

commit_message:
Search snapshot by ID instead of name in Huawei driver

Make huawei_helper.py search for snapshot by its ID instead
of listing all snapshots in range 0-2000 and search by name.

Closes-Bug: #1413511
Change-Id: Ibe008052a0abdac8bea3ba18b3e175947b030479
